<p>The car theft technology purchase relies on choice by the buyer and choice by the seller.  The theft to which it is used for relies on choice by the thief but not by the victim.  This is simple.  The existence of choices adds to wealth.  The denial of choices subtracts wealth.  (See the Econ 101 "deadweight loss" examples I mentioned.)  What happens regarding the wealth of society overall in the case of a car theft is what I've said before: "it depends".  Overall, there is a loss, not because of the transfer from Peter to Paul, but because of all the surrounding activity associated with car theft.</p>

<blockquote>Perhaps you would care to present a different definition?</blockquote>

<p>Perhaps you would care to not make things up.</p>

